* Wolf: Level 3–4 Animal. Howl may cause herbivore panic.
* Giant Crayfish: Level 6–7. Surprise if hiding.
* Giant Killer Frog: Level 3–5 (by HD). Leap and tongue attack.
* Giant Gar: Level 8–9. Swallow on natural 20.
* Ghoul: Level 4–5 Undead. Paralysis (elves immune).
* Zombie: Level 3–4 Undead. Always lose initiative; piercing weapons do only 1 point of damage.

[Nulb Militia]

At any given time, the basically Neutral Evil populace of Nulb can turn out some number of militiamen who are roughly equivalent to bandits (Level 3–5 Fighters, not leaders or exceptional types) in armor and weapons. The total number depends on the circumstances:

* Village threatened with destruction: 60 (possibly over 1,000 gp loot)
* Possibly over 1,000 gp loot: 40
* Minor loot and easy battle prospects: 30
* Village leaders demand service: 20
* Party or force to be attacked is Good: 10

In addition, 5–30 actual brigands are in Nulb and will turn out if their leaders see the situation as lucrative enough. Whether Tolub’s crew is in the village or not, 2–12 additional pirates will likewise participate if the rewards seem worthwhile.

[Coordinated Efforts]

The Evil and Good factions in Nulb are not isolated groups who act randomly and ignore events elsewhere. If one place is attacked, someone is likely to see or hear and spread the word. A serious combat at the Boatmens’ Tavern (area 4), for instance, attracts everyone from the Waterside Hostel (area 1), the citizenry (including 10–40 militiamen), and Otis (area 2), Y’dey, and Murfles (area 3) as well.

Otis, Y’dey, and Murfles are aware of such reactions. In most cases they do not help even Good individuals, for that would reveal their true identities and betray their greater purpose.

All this is not to say that a silent, swift, and deadly attack upon one place or another is always noticed. But if a noisy or protracted fight takes place, the results might prove unpalatable to those causing the problem.

Otis, Y’dey, and Murfles must be handled as rational, clever, intelligent, and thoughtful individuals. They do nothing foolish, nor offer aid to unproven groups. They will not risk losing their cover identities, let alone their lives, for no purpose. Conversely, their participation in a death-stroke to the Temple (an expedition with purpose, planning, sure goals, and solid chances for success) is logical and reasonable.

[In short — play each and every character and group as if you yourself were there.]

[Mercenaries in Nulb]

A handful of men-at-arms are usually in the village and will serve for pay. Because of the repute of the area, these mercenaries are Evil (Neutral or Chaotic) or Chaotic Neutral. Such types are in the village mainly to seek service with some bandit chief or similar person — perhaps even to hire on with a minion of the Temple.

**Mercenary Table 1 (Normal)**
* 1–3: Chaotic Evil
* 4–5: Neutral Evil
* 6: Chaotic Neutral

**Mercenary Table 2 (Party in need of strengthening)**
* 1: Bandits
* 2–3: Neutral Evil mercenaries
* 4–6: Neutral mercenaries

**Leaders**
Mercenaries are led by a 2nd-level Fighter, and if more than six are present, by a 1st-level “serjeant” as well. These leaders form part of the stated group of 5–8.

**Troop Types (Always Present)**
* Light crossbowmen: 2
* Spearmen: All remaining men
* Swordsmen: Leader + Serjeant

**Armor**
* Leader and Serjeant: Chain mail and shield (AC 4)
* Spearmen: Ring mail and shield (AC 6)
* Crossbowmen: Leather armor and shield (AC 7, or AC 8 while firing)

[Assistance and Training]

If Otis requests aid, Burne (at Hommlet) assists magic-users, furnishing them with spells for their books at the cost of 1,000 gp per spell level. He offers only the following spells:

**First Level**
* burning hands
* magic missile
* protection from evil
* shield
* spider climb
* ventriloquism

**Second Level**
* audible glamer
* continual light
* levitate
* ray of enfeeblement
* web

**Third Level**
* dispel magic
* fireball
* suggestion
* tongues

Furthermore, if Otis happens to be along on an adventure during which the true numbers and power of the Temple are revealed, he informs Burne. The latter will, in turn, summon powerful characters from Veluna and Verbobonc. They remain in Hommlet but aid in training and preparing the adventurers to gain levels of experience. Costs are as shown in the PF2e Core Rulebook / GM Core, but time is cut by 50% due to concentrated efforts.

[Nulb - Village]

[Nulb Encounter Key]

The village of Nulb is filthy, ramshackle, and still fairly active despite the destruction of the Temple. The buildings are of turf, mud brick, crudely hewn logs, and old timbers from boats. One or two have stone foundations and proper boards, but even these are in need of repair. The inhabitants of the village are boatmen, fishers, herdsmen, farmers, and the like. It is apparent that no one manages to make much of a living in Nulb, and as it is such a poor place, it is generally ignored by lords and bandits alike.

A small amount of commerce moves along the Low Road, as well as into Nulb from the Velverdyva, as Imeryds Run is wide and deep enough for the small river vessels to use for offloading cargo and likewise embarking it from Nulb, north of the ford there. Only four points in the entire village are noteworthy.

[Area 1 - The Waterside Hostel]

This place is one of the more substantial buildings in Nulb. It has a foundation of field stone and walls of sawn timber, but is nonetheless a scurvy place. Its main trade is in its tavern room, though occasional travelers stop to spend the night. Rich guests have been known to disappear mysteriously.

The hostler is a burly fellow with a scarred, pockmarked visage, one eye covered by a patch. The barkeep is lanky and of greasy appearance, but quite tall. Two slovenly wenches and two manservants of surly mein hover about the place.

Prices are low, however, being only half those of the Inn of the Welcome Wench in Hommlet. (Round down when fixing costs.) In the daytime, only two or three local people can be found in the hostel's tavern room (0-level farmers, laborers, etc.). At night, 14-34 (4d6 + 10) roistering folk can be found in the tavern room (25% villagers, 25% boatmen or bargefolk, 25% transient bandits or mercenaries, 25% river pirates or Temple spies).

* **Hostler: Dick Rentsch** (Level 6–7 Human Fighter)
  AC 7 (leather) or better if time permits. Carries a dagger +1. Has a suit of chain mail +1, shield +1, battle axe +1, and normal longsword hidden in his quarters, along with a trapped iron chest containing significant coinage. Reports to the Temple’s Earth priests.

* **Barman: Wat** (Level 5–6 Human Rogue/Assassin)
  Carries a dagger of venom. Has a shield +1, elven boots, and other hidden gear in his room. Serves the Temple’s Fire priests.

* **Wench: Dala** (Level 4–5 Human Rogue)
  Skilled pickpocket. Has a *philter of love* and jeweled earrings hidden in her room. Is Dick Rentsch’s lover.

* **Wench: Pearl** (Level 4–5 Human Rogue)
  Occasional pickpocket. Has a silver case (worth 75 gp) with a sapphire (1,000 gp) hidden under wax, containing 19 pp. Is Wat’s paramour.

* **Manservants (2)** (Level 3–4 Human Fighters)
  Act as guards. Keep chain mail, shields, light crossbows, and longswords stored in the loft. Work exclusively for the hostler.

[Area 2 - Smithy and Stable]

The smith is a very powerful man, with a bushy beard and large hands forever working some piece of iron. He is assisted by a dull-witted stable 'boy' and a rat-faced young apprentice. Though the smith's main skill is shoeing horses and similar work, he can mend armor and do minor weapons work, and so is kept quite busy. He is usually seen drinking quietly (though he brawls on occasion) at the Waterside Tavern.

* **Chon (Smith's Boy)**: Level 2–3 Human Commoner (Neutral Good). Carries a dagger and a small amount of coin.
* **Sammy (Apprentice Smith)**: Level 3–4 Human Fighter (Neutral). Carries a dagger and coin.
* **Smith: Otis** (Secretly a Level 10+ Ranger Knight, Neutral Good)
  In disguise as an ex-mercenary. Has hidden magical gear (chain mail +2, longsword +2, etc.) and significant wealth beneath the old anvil. He assists Good parties when needed but carefully protects his true identity. He has seven special followers: Murfles (see Area 3), two giant owls, and four sprites who watch the Temple area.

[Area 3 - Mother Screng's Herb Shop]

This dilapidated frame building is well known in the village as the place to go for all sorts of herbs, medicines, and possibly even special draughts of one sort or another. Mother Screng’s daughter appears quite old herself. This daughter, Hruda by name, is quite ugly, and it is no wonder that she is an old maid, for her personality matches her looks and her tongue is sharp.

Inside the shop are counters and shelves filled with jars, flasks, bottles, boxes, and small drawers. These are stuffed with herbs and like stuff, and various infusions and decoctions made from such. Bunches of vegetation of various sorts hang from the rafters or are tossed onto counter tops to dry. The shop has almost every known herb and spice, and even 3 jars of *Keoghtom's ointment* which Mother Screng sells to any adventurers of Good alignment who are in real need of the magic salve, after having proved themselves in expeditions to the Temple.

* **Hruda** (Secretly Murfles, Level 4–5 Elf Fighter/Thief, Neutral Good)
  Otis’ fellow adventurer and follower. Assists Y'dey and reports to Otis. Has hidden adventuring gear and wealth. Will lend silver-tipped arrows to deserving Good adventurers.

* Notes: Murfles has been left to run the shop as Canoness Y’Dey has Joined John, Sasha, Zert and Wonnilon.

[Area 4 - Boatmens' Tavern & Nulb Market]

This large old warehouse building houses a small tavern in a back corner. The remainder of the place is both a warehouse and general store. Various items of soft and hard goods are offered here, as well as general provisions and fresh seafood. The Boatmens' Tavern is as cheap as the bar at the Waterside Hostel — and the place is even dirtier and rougher. The room can hold about 30 customers, and any time after 8:00 AM, 7-12 village folk and half as many rivermen from elsewhere can be found here, tipping mugs of beer, ale, or wine.

[Proprietor: Skole]

Skole is an ex-riverman and smuggler (Level 6–7 Human Fighter, Neutral Evil). He carries a dagger and a topaz and silver ring (worth 300 gp). In the back room he keeps a suit of chain mail, a shield +2, spear +1, and a longsword. A loose brick in the fireplace hides a cache of 10 gems (worth 500 gp each) and a woman’s platinum necklace set with emeralds (worth 8,000 gp).

Skole is assisted by three normal men (Level 3–4 Human Fighters). If time permits, they don scale mail and shield (AC 5) and get shortswords. The toughest also has a light crossbow with 20 bolts. Each has a small purse of coin. They are always working around the place, drinking at the tavern, or asleep in their quarters in a portion of the loft.

[Barmaid: Lodriss]

Lodriss appears to be a normal barmaid (Level 4–5 Human Rogue/Fighter). She carries a normal dagger (tucked into her girdle) and a poisoned dagger (under her skirt). She wears jeweled earrings (worth 400 gp), gold neck chains (worth 120 gp total), four bracelets (values 50, 200, 210, and 500 gp), and a pair of rings (200 and 800 gp).

Lodriss is actually the owner of the Boatmens' Tavern. She is a former camp follower and is now mistress to Tolub (see below), one of the river pirate leaders who frequents Nulb to sell ill-gotten cargoes and to restock supplies.

[Tolub’s Pirate Crew]

Tolub leads a band of 40 river pirates. Only a fourth of his crew is here with him at any time; half are out sailing on the river, and the rest are guarding his ship. If Tolub is not here, his lieutenant Grud probably is, with an identical crew.

To determine who is in port at any given time, roll 1d6:

* 1: Both crews out raiding for 3 days
* 2: Tolub in port for 1 night
* 3: Tolub in port for 2 days
* 4: Grud in port for 1 day
* 5: Both crews in for 1 night (double the crew shown for Tolub)
* 6: Check again, rolling 1d4

Pirate crews are at the tavern only after dark, when three serving wenches are also present. The other 13-18 patrons of the place are 0-level men.

**Tolub** (Level 9–10 Human Fighter, Neutral Evil)
Carries a battle axe +1 and dagger +2. Wears a black opal ring worth 6,000 gp. Has significant personal wealth and is a major power among the river pirates.

**Grud Squinteye** (Level 7–8 Human Fighter, Neutral Evil)
Carries a dagger +1, shortsword, and flail. Wears one earring (worth 600 gp) and a jeweled belt (worth 7,300 gp).

**Pirate Crew Structure** (for either Tolub or Grud — only 1/4 present at the tavern):

* 1st Mate (Level 5–6 Fighter)
* 2nd Mate (Level 5–6 Fighter)
* Bosun (Level 4–5 Fighter)
* 2 Boatswain’s Mates (Level 3–4 Fighters)
* 2–6 Sailors (Level 3–4 Fighters)
* 4–6 Sailors (Level 2–3 Fighters)
* 2–4 Sailors (Level 2–3 Fighters)
* 4 Sailors (Level 2–3 Fighters)

Most sailors wear leather armor and carry spears, battle axes, or daggers. Higher-ranking crew wear chain and carry better weapons.

